ratings.question_text: What is your overall assessment of this course?

narratives.question_text: How would you summarize AFAM 505 01/AMST 643 01 for a fellow student? Would you recommend AFAM 505 01/AMST 643 01 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: If you are interested in either psych or econ, this is a really cool class to learn about some of the most interesting and important aspects of human decision making.
I would recommend it -- it's not an enormous amont of work, and it's a fun seminar in which you'll learn.

This was an interesting overview of some of the important papers/concepts of behavioral economics. I liked that the professor did a fair amount of lecturing, as I didn't often get much out of the class discussions. The assignments were interesting and the professor was responsive to student questions. I wish we had gotten back more assignments (he grades rather harshly), but all in all I am glad I took the course.

I would definitely recommend this class to another student. It was incredibly interesting and I feel as if I learned a great deal about such an important field. Professor Frederick was a great professor.
Good (but not exhaustive) introduction to key literature in behavioral economics.

narratives.question_text: How did this course deepen your knowledge of your discipline/profession? To what extent did this course contribute to your dissertation/research?
comments: I'm an undergrad, and it definitely depened my knowledge -- can't speak to the grad students.
